			<abstract>
				<p>The infinite-layer compound ACuO2 (A = alkaline-earth ions) is regarded as the most suitable material for exploring the fundamental nature of the CuO2 plane because it does not contain a charge-reservoir block, such as a rock-salt or a fluorite like block. We report that superconductivity in the infinite-layer compound Sr0.9La0.1CuO2 is of a three-dimensional nature, in contrast to the quasi two-dimensional superconducting behavior of all other cuprates. The key observation is that the c-axis coherence length is longer than the c-axis lattice constant even at zero temperature. This means that the superconducting order parameter of one CuO2 plane overlaps with those of neighboring CuO2 planes all the temperatures below the Tc. Among all cuprates, only the infinitelayer superconductor shows such a feature.</p>
			</abstract>
